WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.667 --> 00:00:03.920
Now that we've walked through all of the elements of VQE, let's

2
00:00:03.920 --> 00:00:08.173
summarize what we've learned and see how a quantum computer executes it.

3
00:00:09.092 --> 00:00:13.304
We start off with our cleverly chosen reference state, parameterized circuit,

4
00:00:13.555 --> 00:00:16.725
initial choice of parameters and a Hamiltonian.

5
00:00:17.142 --> 00:00:19.477
We pass these to our quantum computer.

6
00:00:20.061 --> 00:00:23.481
Before the Hamiltonian can be executed on the ansatz state,

7
00:00:23.857 --> 00:00:27.360
we need to do classical pre-processing of the circuit

8
00:00:27.527 --> 00:00:32.156
to make it readable by quantum hardware in a process called transpilation.

9
00:00:32.782 --> 00:00:35.744
It's also important to take the most advantage

10
00:00:35.744 --> 00:00:39.956
of the architecture of qubits in the real hardware to get the best results.

11
00:00:40.582 --> 00:00:46.462
These processes are often taken care of automatically so that we don't

12
00:00:46.463 --> 00:00:49.716
explicitly have to know qubit connectivity,

13
00:00:49.716 --> 00:00:52.719
gate fidelities and so on.

14
00:00:52.719 --> 00:00:55.430
Now the task is to measure the resulting state

15
00:00:55.597 --> 00:00:58.850
and estimate the expectation value, which will be further

16
00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:01.061
optimized by a classical optimizer.

17
00:01:01.978 --> 00:01:05.565
This measurement is performed by rotating measurement basis

18
00:01:05.774 --> 00:01:10.445
and then combining the measurement results to obtain the expectation value.

19
00:01:11.154 --> 00:01:13.531
This parameterized result is then fed

20
00:01:13.531 --> 00:01:18.328
into the classical optimizer, which finds new parameters for the state.

21
00:01:19.329 --> 00:01:21.081
Then the process is repeated.

22
00:01:21.081 --> 00:01:24.250
A classical pre-processing creates a new parameterized circuit

23
00:01:24.542 --> 00:01:27.587
and we apply the same Hamiltonian as before.

24
00:01:28.296 --> 00:01:32.383
Note that in the whole VQE process we only change the states

25
00:01:32.592 --> 00:01:36.554
through the parameters which get closer and closer to the ground state.

26
00:01:37.388 --> 00:01:40.809
We repeat this until we're satisfied with the result.

27
00:01:41.559 --> 00:01:42.644
And that's it.

28
00:01:42.644 --> 00:01:47.147
My name is Victoria Lipinska and this was a variational quantum eigensolver course.
